Here is a JavaScript function that uses regular expressions to extract a three character code from a filename in the specified format:

```javascript
function getThreeCharCode(filename) {
const regex = /\d{1,3}[A-Za-z]{0,2}\.[A-Za-z]+\.usfm/;

if (regex.test(filename)) {
return filename.match(/\b\w{1,3}\b/)[0]; // \b word boundary and [0] to get the first match
} else {
throw new Error("Invalid filename format");
}
}
```
This function uses a regular expression pattern that matches one or three digits followed by zero to two uppercase letters, then a dot, then one or more uppercase letters (to ensure the extension is ".usfm"), and finally checks if the entire string matches this pattern. If it does, it returns the first word in the filename using `match()` method with regex as an argument.

You can use this function like so:
```javascript
console.log(getThreeCharCode("57-1Jn.usfm")); // Outputs "1Jn"
console.log(getThreeCharCode("123-AaBbCc.usfm")); // Throws an error because the filename format is invalid
```
